{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Problem ELMo Solves"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Word2Vec and GloVe assign one fixed vector per word type. The word \"bank\" gets the same representation whether it appears in \"river bank\" or \"bank account\". ELMo (Embeddings from Language Models, Peters et al., 2018) produces a different vector for each occurrence of a word, depending on the full sentence context. This solves the polysemy problem that static embeddings cannot address."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "ELMo architecture: tokens pass through a character CNN, then two stacked biLSTM layers (each running forward and backward). The ELMo vector for a word is a learned weighted sum of the character CNN output and both biLSTM layer outputs. Right panel shows 'bank' receiving different vectors in financial vs. geographical contexts."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ELMo is a 3-layer model:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Character CNN"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": produces a token embedding from character n-grams. Handles out-of-vocabulary words and morphological variants (\"running\", \"ran\") without a separate lookup table."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "biLSTM layer 1"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": captures local syntax. The forward and backward passes read the sentence left-to-right and right-to-left; their hidden states are concatenated at each position."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "biLSTM layer 2"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": captures longer-range semantics and disambiguation."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For each word position, ELMo produces a set of three representations "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "{h₀, h₁, h₂}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (one per layer). The final ELMo vector is a learned weighted sum of these:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{ELMo}^{\\text{task}}_k = \\gamma^{\\text{task}} \\sum_{j=0}^{L} s_j^{\\text{task}} \\mathbf{h}_{k,j}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The scalar weights "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "s_j"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (softmax-normalised) and the overall scale "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "γ"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " are learned per downstream task. NER tasks tend to weight lower layers (syntactic) more; coreference resolution weights higher layers (semantic) more."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Training Objective"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "ELMo is pretrained as a bidirectional language model on a large corpus (1B Word Benchmark). It jointly maximises the forward and backward log-likelihoods:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\sum_{k=1}^{N} \\left( \\log P(w_k \\mid w_1, \\ldots, w_{k-1}) + \\log P(w_k \\mid w_{k+1}, \\ldots, w_N) \\right)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This is a biLM (bidirectional language model), but note it is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "not"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the same as BERT's masked language model — the forward and backward LSTMs are trained independently and their outputs are simply concatenated, so each direction only sees tokens on its own side."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using ELMo with AllenNLP"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install allennlp\nfrom allennlp.modules.elmo import Elmo, batch_to_ids\n\n# Pretrained weights from AllenNLP model hub\noptions_file = \"https://allennlp.s3.amazonaws.com/models/elmo/2x4096_512_2048cnn_2xhighway/elmo_2x4096_512_2048cnn_2xhighway_options.json\"\nweight_file  = \"https://allennlp.s3.amazonaws.com/models/elmo/2x4096_512_2048cnn_2xhighway/elmo_2x4096_512_2048cnn_2xhighway_weights.hdf5\"\n\n# num_output_representations = number of different task-specific\n# weighted sums to produce (1 is usual for a single downstream task)\nelmo = Elmo(options_file, weight_file, num_output_representations=1, dropout=0)\n\nsentences = [\n    [\"I\", \"went\", \"to\", \"the\", \"bank\", \"to\", \"deposit\", \"money\"],\n    [\"The\", \"fox\", \"sat\", \"on\", \"the\", \"river\", \"bank\"],\n]\n\n# batch_to_ids converts tokens → character-level ids\ncharacter_ids = batch_to_ids(sentences)   # (batch, seq_len, 50)\noutput = elmo(character_ids)\n\n# embeddings: (batch, seq_len, 1024)\nembeddings = output[\"elmo_representations\"][0]\nprint(embeddings.shape)   # torch.Size([2, 8, 1024])\n\n# The vector for \"bank\" differs between the two sentences\nbank_financial   = embeddings[0, 4]   # sentence 0, position 4\nbank_geographical = embeddings[1, 6]  # sentence 1, position 6\nimport torch\ncos = torch.nn.functional.cosine_similarity\nprint(cos(bank_financial.unsqueeze(0), bank_geographical.unsqueeze(0)))\n# ~0.68 — same word, noticeably different vectors"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using ELMo as Features in a Downstream Model"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The original ELMo paper showed that simply concatenating ELMo vectors to word embeddings in existing models produced large improvements across 6 NLP benchmarks. The standard recipe:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Freeze ELMo weights (no fine-tuning of the biLSTM)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Concatenate ELMo vectors to your task model's input embeddings."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Train only the task model (LSTM / CRF / classifier head) end-to-end."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\nclass NERWithELMo(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, elmo, glove_dim, num_tags):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.elmo = elmo\n        elmo_dim = 1024\n        self.lstm = nn.LSTM(\n            input_size=glove_dim + elmo_dim,\n            hidden_size=256,\n            num_layers=2,\n            batch_first=True,\n            bidirectional=True,\n        )\n        self.classifier = nn.Linear(512, num_tags)\n\n    def forward(self, glove_vecs, character_ids):\n        # glove_vecs: (batch, seq_len, glove_dim)\n        # character_ids: (batch, seq_len, 50)\n        with torch.no_grad():   # freeze ELMo\n            elmo_out = self.elmo(character_ids)[\"elmo_representations\"][0]\n        # Concatenate along feature dimension\n        x = torch.cat([glove_vecs, elmo_out], dim=-1)  # (B, T, glove+1024)\n        h, _ = self.lstm(x)\n        return self.classifier(h)   # (B, T, num_tags)"
          }
        ]
      },
